  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The upper half of a price range above the 0.5 Fibonacci equilibrium (midpoint), representing an overvalued zone. In a bearish bias, it is the preferred area for short entries using PD arrays (order blocks, fair value gaps) at OTE levels (0.618–0.786). Price above reference levels (e.g., midnight open) is also considered premium. Premium zones exist fractally across timeframes.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a price range by marking a swing high and swing low (or wick extremes) and apply a Fibonacci tool; the 0.5 level marks equilibrium, and any price above this is premium.",
    "When the reference candle has an oversized wick, measure 0.5 of the wick alone to define the operative premium boundary.",
    "Reference levels (e.g., midnight open, 8:30 open, daily open) also define premium: price above these levels, especially in a bearish context, is considered premium; price above multiple such levels is deep premium.",
    "Apply the concept fractally: each timeframe and nested range has its own premium zone bounded by its own equilibrium.",
    "Redraw the Fibonacci as the range expands with new higher highs or lower lows to update the equilibrium and premium zone.",
    "Confirm premium zone by observing whether these levels act as resistance (bearish) or support (bullish expansion), often accompanied by a change in state of delivery.",
    "For trade filtering, locate PD arrays (order blocks, fair value gaps, breaker blocks) within premium; for short setups, further narrow the zone using OTE levels (0.618–0.786).",
    "In a non-expansion bullish context, treat any PD array sitting in premium as an invalid entry zone for longs.",
    "Mark the premium zone as the upper half of the range rectangle on the chart for visual reference.",
    "Confirm price is in premium when it trades above the 0.5 level of the defined range."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "When bias is bearish, seek short entries in premium using PD arrays (order blocks, fair value gaps) preferably at OTE levels (0.618–0.786) for enhanced risk-reward. Avoid long entries from premium in a bullish bias unless the market is in a strong expansion phase where premium can act as support; otherwise, wait for a discount retracement. Reference levels (midnight open, etc.) reinforce premium resistance or support. Failure of premium to hold indicates a shift in delivery and bias.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Failing to correctly identify and mark the relevant swing range (e.g., using candle bodies instead of wick extremes, or not distinguishing nested ranges), leading to misclassification of premium vs. discount.",
    "Taking a long entry from a PD array in premium without confirmation of a bullish expansion phase, or during bearish bias, instead of waiting for a discount retracement.",
    "Using premium as a sell zone during an active bullish expansion, fading a strong trend.",
    "Entering shorts right at the 0.5 equilibrium rather than deeper in premium at PD arrays, limiting the risk-reward ratio.",
    "Not redrawing the Fibonacci to update the premium zone when the range expands with new highs/lows.",
    "Continuing to expect premium to hold as support after multiple days of expansion without considering a potential shift in delivery.",
    "Attempting to trade breakouts from premium instead of fading back into the range during confirmed consolidation conditions.",
    "Confusing premium as a standalone sell signal without first confirming that consolidation (Seek and Destroy) conditions are present — premium/discount analysis is context-dependent.",
    "Entering long in the Premium Zone during an uptrend/bullish market, resulting in poor risk-to-reward.",
    "Shorting from the Discount Zone in a bearish market instead of Premium Zone.",
    "Entering prematurely without lower timeframe confirmation of a reversal signal."
  ],
